The one that really looks interesting.. with defense and military use cases is Skyworks. Go research them.

I only just heard about Archer about a week ago and now it's partnered.

I fear that it might be the best of the bunch with nearer term start and United partnership, so I might sell if QELL, ZNTE or RTP (I hold all) get one of these "also rans." 

The valuation for Joby mentioned is too high at $10 and much to high at $15+ 

There's an article about Lilium from ex-employees that says things are not well inside the company.

The one that really looks interesting.. with defense and military use cases is Skyworks. Go research them.

author: peter-doubt
body:
5G is more industrial automation than consumer communication.

Stop looking at the handheld devices.. look to the infrastructure.  Yesterday you missed SWKS.. almost 10% markup in one day. Their market includes AAPL .. but potentially much more. 

In a broad sense, semiconductors and broadband telecommunications... Routing... Cloud and higher technology applications.  (AI traffic analysis... for example).

Step away from the cell phone and see what else runs interactively on the web.

 Qorvo is expected to post a 23% increase in revenue for the December quarter on Wednesday, according to consensus analyst forecasts.

Do you think any of these stocks is a good buy right now and can skyrocket  🚀 ?

author: peter-doubt
body:
The stocks you mention are end users... You would do better with unique suppliers.

They're also entangled in the shortage of semiconductors... My move was to SMH... ETF for semiconductors... And SWKS.. chip design for radio frequency required for 5G.

Consider that 5G speeds will benefit high bandwidth consumption... Thus high resolution graphics. For that, Nvidia. 

And what I've seen is far more interactive... Distant operation of robotic factories?

author: ufos8mycat
body:
Hey all, I'm very new to trading, had always wanted to dive in but never really have the disposable income to do so.

I know it can be a risky move, especially for those who don't really have money to play with. But with apps like Robinhood making it a bit simpler to get into the game and buy/sell etc. I figured I'd finally try my luck.

Now I know there's some out there that can drop a few thousand into the market like it's nothing and move from there. However I'm not in that boat and so taking risky chances with what I do have to throw in on a chance that something will jump up is a harder decision for someone like me. At my current rate I figure I can throw in about $50 a week or so, and sometimes more depending on the money I have coming in.

I was wondering what some might think of the decisions I made, based on me assuming the companies I bought into being more 'safe bets' compared to some other options. The stocks I had bought, along with how much I put in (It will be added to and adjusted more evenly over time) are as follows:

**Skyworks (SWKS) - $5**  
**Intel (INTC) - $5**  
**Nvidia (NVDA) - $5**  
**Microsoft (MSFT) - $5**  
**Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing (TSM) - $30**

Nvidia is the one I was most unsure on after buying it, but with what seems like everyone buying GPUs these days, along with a mining surge again, I figured it'd be an okay pick. Not necessarily looking for advice or any of that in the sense of making a bad investment based off of something someone may suggest. Just the thoughts on my choices and possibly adding more to these in the future.

Other options I had considered were Amazon, Apple, and Google. But was unsure on how they would react as the pandemic begins to disappear eventually.

author: peter-doubt
body:
5G is more industrial automation than consumer communication.

Stop looking at the handheld devices.. look to the infrastructure.  Yesterday you missed SWKS.. almost 10% markup in one day. Their market includes AAPL .. but potentially much more. 

In a broad sense, semiconductors and broadband telecommunications... Routing... Cloud and higher technology applications.  (AI traffic analysis... for example).

Step away from the cell phone and see what else runs interactively on the web.
